Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Bamako - Malian health authorities say they are searching for two women who left Guinea after having had contact with a recent Ebola case.Dr Keni Diarra, head doctor at the health centre in Kenieba in the Kayes region, said on Wednesday the two Guinean women came to Mali on Sunday. He said they are suspected to be in Hamdallaye, a village in Kayes.The World Health Organization says there have been eight cases of Ebola and seven deaths since late February in Guinea, flare-ups that came months after the nation was declared Ebola-free.In Mali eight people were infected with Ebola and six of them died in 2014 before it was declared free from transmissions in January 2015.More than 11 300 people, mostly in West Africa, have died from Ebola since December 2013.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.